## 🐛 Key Challenges Solved

- Configured AWS credentials for Docker containers running inside Jenkins
- Resolved ECR authentication in non-interactive Jenkins pipeline
- Implemented build-number tagging for full image traceability in ECR
- Mounted AWS credentials securely without hardcoding in source code
- Configured swap space on t2.small to handle Jenkins + Docker build load

---

## 💼 Interview Talking Points

**What problem does this solve?**
> Fraud detection is a critical banking requirement. This system automates the detection and alerting process — transactions are analysed the moment they are uploaded, suspicious ones are flagged, stored and reported with no manual intervention.

**Why Jenkins and Docker?**
> Jenkins automates the entire build, test and deploy process. Docker ensures the application runs identically in every environment — development, testing and production.

**Why ECR instead of Docker Hub?**
> ECR is a private AWS registry — more secure for banking applications. It integrates natively with AWS IAM for access control and with EC2 for fast image pulls within the same region.

**What happens when fraud is detected?**
> The transaction is flagged by the rules engine, saved to DynamoDB for audit purposes, and an email alert is sent via SNS to the fraud investigation team — all within seconds.

